	<span id="content"></span>
	<main>
		<img width="2048" height="984" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-robots-and-war-munitions.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="munition on the sea floor" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-robots-and-war-munitions.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-robots-and-war-munitions-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-robots-and-war-munitions-1200x577.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-robots-and-war-munitions-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-robots-and-war-munitions-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-robots-and-war-munitions-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2048px) 100vw, 2048px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Germany’s North and Baltic Seas are littered with munitions from the First and Second World Wars, such as shells—as shown here—once fired from German battleships. Photo courtesy of SeaTerra</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">The Big Baltic Bomb Cleanup</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">The ocean became a dumping ground for weapons after Allied forces defeated the Nazis. Now a team of robots and divers are making the Baltic Sea safer.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/paul-hockenos/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Paul Hockenos</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						September 5, 2024 | 2,700 words, about 14 minutes
					</aside>

					
